TY  - JOUR
T1  - Fact: The Form of Participation Does Matter—A Rebuttal to Leana, Locke, and Schweiger
AU  - Cotton, John L.
AU  - Vollrath, David A.
AU  - Lengnick-Hall, Mark L.
AU  - Froggatt, Kirk L.
Y1  - 1990/01/01
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1990.4308291
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1990.4308291
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 147
EP  - 153
VL  - 15
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In responding to the critique by Leana, Locke, and Schweiger (1990) of our review, we identify points of confusion and misunderstanding, disagreements in judgment, and comments with which we agree. Our original conclusion stands: The form of participation influences the effectiveness of that participation. Leana et al. simply show that excluding certain forms of participation from consideration yields results that are considerably different. We discuss how their critique demonstrates the importance of clarity, as well as judgment decisions, in research reviews.
AB  - In responding to the critique by Leana, Locke, and Schweiger (1990) of our review, we identify points of confusion and misunderstanding, disagreements in judgment, and comments with which we agree. Our original conclusion stands: The form of participation influences the effectiveness of that participation. Leana et al. simply show that excluding certain forms of participation from consideration yields results that are considerably different. We discuss how their critique demonstrates the importance of clarity, as well as judgment decisions, in research reviews.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1990.4308291
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1990.4308291
