TY  - JOUR
T1  - Causal Ambiguity, Barriers to Imitation, and Sustainable Competitive Advantage
AU  - Reed, Richard
AU  - DeFillippi, Robert J.
Y1  - 1990/01/01
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1990.4308277
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1990.4308277
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 88
EP  - 102
VL  - 15
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article addresses the issues of competitive advantage and competitor imitation. It is argued that tacitness, complexity, and specificity in a firm's skills and resources can generate causal ambiguity in competency-based advantage, and thus raise barriers to imitation. Reinvestment in causally ambiguous competencies is necessary to protect the advantage. Without reinvestment, attritional effects of continued competitive action will cause decay in the barriers to imitation. From this theorizing, research propositions are suggested, which, ultimately, will lead to an improved understanding of competitive advantage sustainability.
AB  - This article addresses the issues of competitive advantage and competitor imitation. It is argued that tacitness, complexity, and specificity in a firm's skills and resources can generate causal ambiguity in competency-based advantage, and thus raise barriers to imitation. Reinvestment in causally ambiguous competencies is necessary to protect the advantage. Without reinvestment, attritional effects of continued competitive action will cause decay in the barriers to imitation. From this theorizing, research propositions are suggested, which, ultimately, will lead to an improved understanding of competitive advantage sustainability.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1990.4308277
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1990.4308277
Y2  - 2026/04/24
ER  - 

